<definition xml:id="def-slope">
  <statement>
    <p>
      The <term>slope</term> of a line is a number that represents the direction and steepness of the line. For a linear function, the slope never changes - meaning it is a constant average rate of change.
    </p>
  </statement>
</definition>

<activity xml:id="LR-5-Compare-Slopes-of-Lines">
<introduction>
  <p>
    The steepness of a line depends on the vertical and horizontal distances between two points on the line. Use the graph below to compare the steepness, or slope, of the two lines.
  </p>
  <image xml:id="comparing-slopes-of-lines">
    <sageplot>
      f(x) = (1/2)*x-1
      g(x) = 4*x-3
      p=plot(f, (x, -10, 10), ymin=-10, ymax=10, color='blue', thickness=3,  gridlines=[[-10..15],[-10..10]]) + point((0,-1),size=40,xmin=-10,xmax=15,ymin=-10,ymax=10)+ point((4,1),size=40,xmin=-10,xmax=15,ymin=-10,ymax=10) + plot(g, (x, -10, 10), ymin=-10, ymax=10, color='red', thickness=3) + point((0,-3),size=40,xmin=-10,xmax=15,ymin=-10,ymax=10, color='red')+ point((2,5),size=40,xmin=-10,xmax=15,ymin=-10,ymax=10, color='red')
      p
    </sageplot>
  </image>
</introduction>
<task>
  <statement>
    <p>
      What is the vertical distance between the two points on the red line?
    </p>
  </statement>
</task>
<task>
  <statement>
    <p>
      What is the horizontal distance between the two points on the red line?
    </p>
  </statement>
</task>
<task>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Using information from parts <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>, what value could we use to describe the steepness of the red line?
    </p>
  </statement>
</task>
<task>
  <statement>
    <p>
      What is the vertical distance between the two points on the blue line?
    </p>
  </statement>
</task>
<task>
  <statement>
    <p>
      What is the horizontal distance between the two points on the blue line?
    </p>
  </statement>
</task>
<task>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Using information from parts <m>d</m> and <m>e</m>, what value could we use to describe the steepness of the blue line?
    </p>
  </statement>
</task>
<task>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Which line is the steepest?
    </p>
  </statement>
</task>
</activity>

<remark>
  The steepness, or slope, of a line can be found by the change in <m>y</m> (the vertical distance between two points on the line) divided by the change in <m>x</m> (the horizontal distance between two points on the line). Slope can be calculated as "rise over run."
  <p>
    How steep a line is also depends on the value of the slope. The red line in <xref ref="LR-5-Compare-Slopes-of-Lines"/> has a larger value for it's slope than the blue line. Thus, the red line is steeper than the blue line.
  </p>
</remark>

<activity xml:id="Direction-and-slope">
  <introduction>
    <p>
     Now that we know how to find the slope (or steepness) of a line, let's look at other properties of slope. Use the graph below to answer the following questions. 
    </p>
    <image xml:id="comparing-direction-of-lines">
      <sageplot>
        f(x) = (1/2)*x-1
        g(x) = -(1/2)*x-1
        p=plot(f, (x, -10, 10), ymin=-10, ymax=10, color='blue', thickness=3, gridlines=[[-10..10],[-10..10]]) + plot(g, (x, -10, 10), ymin=-10, ymax=10, color='green', thickness=3, gridlines=[[-10..10],[-10..10]])
        p
      </sageplot>
    </image>
  </introduction>
  <task>
    <statement>
      <p>
        What is the slope of the blue line?
      <ol marker= "A." cols="2">
        <li><m>\frac{1}{2}</m></li>
        <li><m>2</m></li>
        <li><m>-\frac{1}{2}</m></li>
        <li><m>-2</m></li></ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        A: <m>\frac{1}{2}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
  </task>
  <task>
    <statement>
      <p>
        What is the slope of the green line?
      <ol marker= "A." cols="2">
        <li><m>\frac{1}{2}</m></li>
        <li><m>2</m></li>
        <li><m>-\frac{1}{2}</m></li>
        <li><m>-2</m></li></ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        C: <m>-\frac{1}{2}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
  </task>
  <task>
    <statement>
      <p>
        How are the slopes of the lines similar?
      </p>
    </statement>
  </task>
  <task>
    <statement>
      <p>
        How are the slopes of the lines different?
      </p>
    </statement>
  </task>
</activity>

<remark>
  Notice in <xref ref="Direction-and-slope"/> that the slope does not just indicate how steep a line is, but also it's direction. A negative slope indicates that the line is decreasing (from left to right) and a positive slope indicates that the line is increasing (from left to right).
</remark>

<activity xml:id="Calculating-slope-from-two-points">
  <introduction>
    <p>
      Suppose <m>(-3,7)</m> and <m>(7,2)</m> are two points on a line.
    </p>
  </introduction>
  <task>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Plot these points on a graph and find the slope by using "rise over run."
      </p>
    </statement>
  </task>
  <task>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Now calculate the slope by using the change in <m>y</m> over the change in <m>x</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </task>
  <task>
    <statement>
      <p>
        What do you notice about the slopes you got in parts <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>?
      </p>
    </statement>
  </task>
</activity>

<remark>
  We can calculate slope by finding the change in <m>y</m> and dividing by the change in <m>x</m>. Mathematically, this means that when given <m> (x_{1},y_{1})</m> and <m> (x_{2}, y_{2})</m>, <me>slope=\frac{y_{2}-y_{1}}{x_{2}-x_{1}}</me>.
</remark>

